{\"root_cause\":\"The orders container was configured with CHUNK_BYTES=1048576 and no CACHE_MAX, so each /orders request retained another 1 MiB chunk in an unbounded in-memory cache. Under the load generator this exceeded the container's 256 MiB memory limit, causing repeated cgroup OOM kills with exit code 137 and intermittent checkout failures.\",\"actions_taken\":\"Confirmed sreft-orders was in a restart loop and Docker inspect showed OOMKilled=true, ExitCode=137, and a 256 MiB memory cap. Reviewed logs and docker-compose.yaml, which showed orders running with an unbounded cache while payments used CACHE_MAX=16. Updated only the orders service environment to set CACHE_MAX=16, recreated only sreft-orders with docker compose up -d orders, then verified /orders responses, Docker state, and memory usage under load. After the fix, orders remained running, OOMKilled=false, retained_chunks=16, and memory stayed around 46 MiB of 256 MiB.\",\"postmortem\":\"A service-level memory leak was allowed into the orders deployment because the cache bound was omitted, and the restart policy converted OOM kills into intermittent availability instead of a clear hard failure. The immediate remediation was to bound the cache consistently with the stable payments service. Follow-up should make bounded cache settings mandatory or default-safe, add a startup/config validation for unbounded cache in production, and alert on OOMKilled/restart-loop signals before customer checkout errors accumulate.\"}
EOF"
